301","1268–1316":"1268–1316","1281–1318":"1281–1318","1264–1300":"1264–1300","1282–1318":"1282–1318","1290–Male":"1290–Deceased","1212–1284":"1212–1284","1216–Female":"1216–Deceased","1264":"1264","1284":"1284","1282":"1282","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1216":"1216","1238":"1238","Abt 1282":"about 1282","1257":"1257","1268":"1268","1301":"1301","1300":"1300","1212":"1212","about 1268":"about 1268","ABT 1290":"about 1290","1318":"1318","Schwerin, Mecklenburg-Schwerin, Prussia, Germany":"Schwerin, Teltow, Brandenburg, Prussia, Germany","of, Lindau, Magdeburg, Germany":"Lindau, Weißenfels, Saxony-Anhalt, Germany","Berlin, Brandenburg, Prussia, Germany":"Berlin, Brandenburg, Prussia","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lindau","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","German: habitational name from Lindau, which is named with Old High German <i>linta</i> ‘lime tree’ + <i>ouwa</i> ‘water meadow’ or ‘island’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lindauer","meanings":["German: habitational name for someone from Lindau (see   Lindau  )."]}]},{"name":"Ulrich","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>uodal</i> ‘riches’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power’; the name of two major German saints,  Ulrich of Augsburg  (  d. 973 ) and  Ulrich of Cluny  (  <i>c.</i>1018–93 ), and the Blessed Ulrich of Einsiedeln in Switzerland (  d. <i>c.</i>980 )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Count","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>counte</i> ‘count’ (Old French <i>conte</i>, from Latin <i>comes</i>, <i>comitem</i>); a title of French and Norman nobility, ranking as equivalent to English   Earl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Earl","meanings":["North American: from the title originally adopted as a nickname parallel to   Duke  ,   King  , etc. The title was used in England in Norman times as an equivalent of the French <i>comte</i> ‘count’ it is from Old English <i>eorl</i> ‘warrior, nobleman, prince’. In some cases the given name may have been taken from the surname <i>Earl</i>, which was originally either a nickname or a term denoting someone who worked in the household of an earl."]}]},{"name":"von","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Ronald .  It is sometimes used as a given name in its own right."],"variants":[{"name":"Ronald","meanings":["From the Old Norse personal name <i>Rögnvaldr</i> (composed of <i>regin</i> ‘advice, decision’ (also, ‘the gods’) + <i>valdr</i> ‘ruler’). This name was regularly used in the Middle Ages in northern England and Scotland, where Scandinavian influence was strong. It is now widespread throughout the English-speaking world."]}]},{"name":"Ruppin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Tuppen  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tuppen","meanings":["English: nickname, possibly from an unrecorded diminutive of Middle English  <i>top</i>, Anglo-Norman French  <i>toup</i>,  <i>tupe</i>,  <i>tup</i> ‘forelock, tuft of hair on the top of the head’, formed with the suffix  <i>-in</i>.  Compare  Tupp  ,   Topping  ,   Topper  , and   Tupper  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ulrich Count von Ruppin Lindau was born about 1268, in Lindau, Weißenfels, Saxony-Anhalt, Germany, his father, Gunther I Count of Lindau, was 58 and his mother, Eufemie von Rügen, was 54. He had at least 2 sons with Elisabeth Countess Of Holstein. He died in 1316, at the age of 49."},"et":{"about 1268–1316":"umbes 1268–1316","1238–1301":"1238–1301","1268–1316":"1268–1316","1281–1318":"1281–1318","1264–1300":"1264–1300","1282–1318":"1282–1318","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1212–1284":"1212–1284